ce:section.ce:para:
The MO degradation kinetics by the composite CNDs films were studied where the concentration of MO was quantified at the absorbance peak maxima (Regression analysis wavelength: MO = 523 nm). Results show that the reactive chemical degradation for MO followed the pseudo first-order kinetics. Fig. 6 showed the curve fitting of the change in At normalized by A0 with reaction time, where Ao is the initial absorbance of dye solution and At is the absorbance at different time intervals. The degradation process fits very well to the first-order exponential decay kinetics;
A/A0 = exp (−kt)
where k (min−1) is the observed rate constant, and t is the reaction time. The rate constant for the degradation process by CND composite films are shown in Fig. 6 (inset). The ɩ-carr-CND film measured the higher rate constant showing a good degradation activity towards MO. This can be attributed to the stability showed by the ɩ-carr-CND film measured by zeta potential compared to ᴋ-carr-CND and λ-carr-CND films.
